I"II<p>James Song</p>

<p>Two Stories of Discernment.</p>

<p>Father Cho</p>

<p>So—discernment!</p>

<p>I had to discern when I was finishing up my master’s theology at Berkeley.</p>

<p>All my friends and professors saw I had talent and potential in academia. I was pretty set on getting a Ph.D. in missiology, the study of missions. My career was set: I would be a professor at Sogang University, the Jesuit university in Seoul. As you know, in Korea, there’s a lot of prestige in being a professor.</p>

<p>Then the Filipino superior in charge of Southeast Asia missions called me one day and told me I had to come back to Cambodia right away. I was part of that mission and it needed me. But that would mean I’d have to give up on the Ph.D. Can you imagine the chaos I was going through? They gave me some time and told me it was up to me to discern.</p>

<p>I went on an eight-day retreat at the Jesuit retreat house in Palo Alto. It’s a beautiful place.</p>

<p>I prayed five hours a day, according to what the retreat master assigned me.</p>

<p>Nothing happened.</p>

<p>I was so frustrated. Many desires came up, including selfish desires and anger at the superior for calling me to come back at a critical time like this. This went on for five days.</p>

<p>On the sixth day, I couldn’t bring myself to pray. I was exhausted. I thought I’d go for a walk in that beautiful place, in that beautiful nature—you should go there sometime. I took the Bible verse that the retreat master gave me: it was the Psalm that goes “as the deer pants for water, my soul thirsts for you.”<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote" rel="footnote" role="doc-noteref">1</a></sup></p>

<p>After five days of dry prayer, the moment I laid eyes on that passage, there was total peace and joy in my heart. All the voices and desires in me became quiet. I was consoled with this peace the entire day. Now I could listen to God.</p>

<p>On the seventh day, I went for another walk. Then, out of nowhere, in that beautiful forest, I saw the faces of the people I had met in Cambodia. I didn’t know what was happening—I thought it was an illusion. I saw the school children I had met, the lady who got a heart attack and passed away—I saw their faces one by one.</p>

<p>Then, among the faces, I heard something. It was a voice. “I am here,” it said. “I need you.” It was the voice of Jesus.</p>

<p>I cried many tears of gratitude and joy. About two hours passed before I got up. I knew where my heart was.</p>

<p>The next day was the last day of retreat. My discernment wasn’t finished. We still need what we call “confirmation.” This is very important. It can come in many forms. For me, my retreat master told me to ask God directly for confirmation. So I did. And the moment I came to pray, there was overwhelming peace and joy about what was in my heart.</p>

<p>It was time to go back to Berkeley. The retreat master said there would be trouble when I go back, and he told me to prepare myself for that. I went back, and sure enough my friends and professors thought I was crazy. This confused me, but the peace in my heart was firm. I went back to Cambodia soon after.</p>

<p>Your discernment is not about whether you will volunteer at the school another year or leave. It’s about your vocation—what you will do. If you want to be a missionary, you will gain a lot of experience here. If you want to be a pianist, you should go somewhere where you can pursue that. If you want to be a professor, you should go back to school.</p>

<p>My identity is clear: I am a Jesuit. Our big goal is the greater glory of God. But we have to discern the special purpose in our lives to accomplish this. When that purpose is discerned, we can easily decide on the means to get to that purpose for the greater glory of God.</p>

<p>What do you want to do?</p>

<p>Some years after I had gone back to Cambodia, there was a change in leadership, and the new superior had a bigger vision for the Southeast Asia missions. They assigned me to study Buddhism, so I was able to study Buddhism in Sri Lanka, and not only study it, but practice it there, too. After that, the mission needed an expert in interreligious dialogue, so I was sent to England for a doctorate in interreligious dialogue—between Buddhism and Christianity. Now I get to use my knowledge in a very practical way in my work.</p>

<p>There is peace with what you’ve discerned, no matter what people say. If you’re still switching back-and-forth, that’s not the result of true discernment. People usually react to life; they don’t discern. God will give you a definite answer if you are sincere.</p>

<p>Discernment, in Broad Strokes</p>

<p>The process of discernment (of spirits) developed by St. Ignatius, the founder of the Jesuits, “is not about choosing between good and bad,” as Father Cho once told me. In that case, there is nothing to discern—you simply choose what is good. Discernment is about choosing the better among good options.</p>

<p>Which among good options serves God and others best?</p>

<p>For the sake of a greater goal, you must be indifferent to all things: health, money, honor, longevity, and everything else. All these you keep or toss for the sake of God’s greater glory. They are secondary things,</p>

<p>Protestants talk in a similar way about decision-making with the Holy Spirit. They say, “God put it in my heart to do this,” or, “I asked God to put in me a heart for this,” or, “I prayed and felt peace about this.”</p>

<p>Some people receive a special, non-religious calling. I have a friend, a culturally Catholic European woman in her fifties, who, in her first semester as a Ph.D. student at Columbia, dropped her studies to serve in Haiti after the 2010 earthquake. Everyone around her thought she was crazy. “I was completely at peace,” she said. This led to other service projects, and her journey brought her to Cambodia, where I met her. I think she is living a very authentic life.</p>

<p>In the Ignatian tradition, the <a href="https://www.ignatianspirituality.com/making-good-decisions/an-approach-to-good-choices/an-ignatian-framework-for-making-a-decision/">discernment process</a> will lead you to a definite and authentic decision that is accompanied by spiritual consolation.</p>

<p>There are some other voices I’ve heard. A younger Korean Jesuit told me that in our decision-making, “God respects our freedom.” A Japanese Jesuit, the funniest Jesuit I’ve met, commented as much to himself as to me that “it’s dangerous to be too certain about who you are. What does it mean to be a Jesuit? I’m not sure I’m really a Jesuit.” St. Ignatius talked about ongoing discernment as well as informative spiritual desolation. There is also something one priest calls “<a href="https://www.americamagazine.org/faith/2019/11/04/practical-guide-discernment-hint-just-be-yourself/">sufficient certainty</a>” for a decision.</p>

<p>*</p>

<p>My Discernment</p>

<p>After the conversation with Father Cho, I decided to discern again. The school year was coming to a close, and I let people know that I’d be leaving. Still, I prayed and meditated daily for indifference. The good, the bad, the doubts, the hopes, the things that gave me life and the things that made me feel stuck—I offered everything to God. I spent four months in prayer, talking to priests who generously listened and guided me.</p>

<p>There were some insights that helped me become more indifferent.</p>

<p>One was not to force something good. “You do not delight in sacrifice, or I would bring it; you do not take pleasure in burnt offerings. My sacrifice, O God, is a broken spirit; a broken and contrite heart you, God, will not despise.”<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" class="footnote" rel="footnote" role="doc-noteref">2</a></sup> The rest of the Psalm says that love comes before labor that God accepts.<sup id="fnref:3"><a href="#fn:3" class="footnote" rel="footnote" role="doc-noteref">3</a></sup></p>

<p>I meditated on the Ignatian idea of magis, meaning “more” or “greater” in Latin. If I stayed, can I offer not great service, but greater and total service? Was my heart fully in it?</p>

<p>Another is the idea that nothing belongs to me: my life, my talents, my time, my health, my youth—none of it is mine.<sup id="fnref:4"><a href="#fn:4" class="footnote" rel="footnote" role="doc-noteref">4</a></sup></p>

<p>Finally, meditating on the <a href="https://www.bc.edu/content/dam/files/offices/ministry/pdf/First%20Principle%20and%20Foundation%20-March%202015%20%282%29.pdf">“Principles and Foundations”</a> of Spiritual Exercises by Saint Ignatius also helped.</p>

<p>I reasoned that the best thing I could do for the world might be to stay: my community needed English teachers and native English speakers, who are rare in rural Cambodia. I was familiar with the Jesuits. Personally, it was an education just being around them, intellectually and spiritually. They cared for each person they served and didn’t count the cost. Their heart for the mission was pure. Theologically, I grew up a conservative Presbyterian. Living with Jesuits was like a bottle of cold beer after a marathon.</p>

<p>Other good things. My Cambodian language was coming along. I had just gotten past some culture-clashes with my colleagues, whom I admired and who liked me. My Khmer friends loved me with a pure love I had not felt before. I played trumpet for the Mass twice a week, which was a blast. The children I taught were the joy of my life. I learned that letting go of the self and giving my time and energy is a joy, and my community was a great place to give.</p>

<p>“There’s nothing to discern,” some fathers would point out. “Just stay!”</p>

<p>“If you stay,” a teacher-friend said, “you can see my son.” I had just met her four-year-old daughter, whom she had been talking my ears off about for a year. She was planning to have another baby.</p>

<p>“You can learn more about the students,” the English program coordinator told me. Because of the rough school experience she had growing up in a rural village nearby, she had great passion for education and children. Everyone respected and adored her.</p>

<p>“Stay at the school a year longer,” another Khmer friend advised me. “You’ll be in a better place to get a master’s or a new job.”</p>

<p>“Cambodian children need you,” my best Cambodian friend, a teacher in Phnom Penh, messaged me.</p>

<p>“You create people,” said another Khmer teacher, a man who loved me and would do anything for me. “Stay one more year. I beg you.”</p>

<p>My life was simple: wake up, prepare lessons, lunch with priests and volunteers, play tag with children, teach English, play trumpet, dinner with friends, some more students, a podcast, exercise and sleep. I had Saturdays off, and on Sundays I went to Mass and taught students in the afternoon. It was a good little life. The kingdom of God is a mustard seed… One more year would be an opportunity.</p>

<p>I considered the hard things, too: the triple-digit weather without air conditioning in the office and the classrooms, the dozens of mosquito bites I get every trumpet session in the outdoor hall, the rural setting that was starting to wear me out, the slow progress in students’ English acquisition, the occasional stomach issues from food, the smallness of what I was doing when I could be more effective elsewhere, and everything I could be doing in the U.S.</p>

<p>I had an income from the volunteer stipend and teaching online, but no savings and nothing I could contribute, emotionally or financially, to my family. I was having hair loss—from the water, I think—and severe allergies, especially when the country was covered in smoke in January from the yearly burning of rice fields.</p>

<p>All of these things figured into my thoughts through the four months of discernment. I felt settled in Cambodia, but I was uncomfortable physically. In the U.S., it is flipped: I feel fine physically, but I’m pushed to find mission-driven community and work.</p>

<p>Maybe it is this simple: discernment is listening to the voice that nudges us toward renewal when our lives need movement. We don’t know what we don’t know.</p>

<p>I asked for indifference. I could lose some hair—I’m still young, it’ll grow back—and play trumpet with mosquitoes and spend January a little dizzy. The mission here may be how I could labor for God’s greater glory and serve others best. I was ready for it, if I were to stay. And if I were to leave, I would leave with nothing but thanks and find other meaningful work. I had been blessed with a community of uncommon love—the Jesuits themselves said it was one of the best in their experience—but I didn’t have to cling on to it. I have a model of what works, so I could go and give to a new community.</p>

<p>I was ready to listen.</p>

<p>Over the four months, there were three big “movements” in my heart. I sat with the changes. Each movement dug deeper than the one before. They were movements from self to God and others.</p>

<p>I prayed for the heart to stay. It was reasonable to stay, and for several weeks, I felt it right to stay. But gradually, with the self coloring the meditation less and less, it dawned on me that I’d be forcing a good thing that wasn’t in my heart.</p>

<p>What I’d do and where I’d go wasn’t clear, but this didn’t discourage me.</p>

<p>One night, I had a late dinner with the priest closest to me in the community.</p>

<p>“What are you passionate about?” he asked. I told him. “I could tell,” he said. “Did you thank God about it?” I hadn’t. “Start with that.”</p>

<p>*</p>

<p>Ongoing Discernment</p>

<p>Then I came across <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Mark%205&amp;version=GNT">Mark 5</a>.</p>

<p>There was a man who lived in the tombs, cut himself with stones, could not be held down by chains or by people, and roamed about the tombs and the surrounding hills naked. In today’s terms, we might say the man suffered from extreme cases of clinical depression, self-hatred, impulse control disorder, and antisocial personality disorder. He “had an evil spirit in him”, many demons named Legion. Jesus healed him with his loving words and deeds.</p>

<p>This was what I experienced in Cambodia for two years. The broken man was me, and Cambodian children with their beautiful smiles, friends that loved me with deep and generous love, strangers who welcomed me like their brother—they were Jesus the loving healer.</p>

<p>The man, after being healed, begged to follow Jesus. Jesus said no. He had a different mission for the man: “Go back home to your family and tell them how much the Lord has done for you and how kind he has been to you.”</p>

<p>The man went to his family and friends and, giving fully, went “all through the Ten Towns, telling what Jesus had done for him.”</p>

<p>Jesus discerned that it would be better for the man to go back home rather than join Jesus on the road. He had compassion for the broken man and his broken family.</p>

<p>What if I went home, too? There were some bonds in the family that needed strengthening, some needs that could be filled. I hadn’t had the mental and emotional resources to be a good son and brother. I was ready to start sharing.</p>

<p>I am in Korea now, with my family.</p>

<p>*</p>

<p>Notes:</p>

<ul>
  <li>I could fly anywhere if something happened. When the Cambodia-Thailand border dispute started, American Peace Corp volunteers in my province, which borders Thailand, were evacuated to a city farther away from the border for several days, while all Korean volunteers in Cambodia were evacuated to the capital for two weeks. Jesuits, some missionaries, and Cambodian citizens—children, mothers, teachers, etc.—all stayed.</li>
  <li>I had weekends off. Many of my teacher friends had all-day classes on weekends for their bachelor’s or master’s on top of longer-than-full-time work during the week. Some had families, too. It was the only way to make things work. I, on the other hand, was given all the flexibility I requested.</li>
  <li>Here’s the salary breakdown, from my knowledge from the street: a factory worker makes about $180 per month, a full-time teacher of a private school around $300, a hospitality worker as low as $100, an employee at a foreign NGO can make $500 or more, and a doctor can make anywhere from $300 to $2,000 or more. English teachers, working less hours with less expertise and years of education, can make $2,500 or higher.</li>
  <li>Volunteers had the option of installing air conditioning in their rooms. Only one of my Cambodian friends in the rural area had air conditioning.</li>
  <li>If my motorcycle broke, I could get a new one for $600-$700.</li>
</ul>

<p>Some of my Cambodian friends are more compassionate, hard-working, intelligent, and generous than I am—are they less deserving of good things? Why do I get to enjoy these privileges? We can think about it more simply, as some Jesuits do: we develop our gifts to the fullest to give them away totally and most effectively for the greater glory of God. Rational and fulfilling, right? Are there any contenders to this for a really meaningful life?</p>
